Unfettered central bankers?
Prague - recently, they were universally criticized in the developed world.
The main points of attack are roughly as follows: central bankers have been too active since 2008, and their powers have expanded too fast, which is harming the economy.
This claim - — it is quite strange that it is popular in both the ideologically incoherent camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists — — is completely wrong.
Critics failed to understand that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation, but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Prices are like a person's body temperature, which can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing severe symptoms.
When fighting off deflation caused by weak demand and curbing inflation driven by excessive demand, the central bank must be equally "active" as well.
Despite the battle being completely symmetrical, the public's assessment of this is oddly severely biased, especially in countries where people are very conservative with their finances.
My homeland of the Czech Republic is one of them. Savers in the Czech Republic have a very small savings scale, and the loan-to-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs fear inflation, even though Czech inflation rate reached its lowest point in 13 years last year and the Czech National Bank, in which I served as vice governor since 2013, has been committed to eliminating the risk of deflation.
Other common complaints about central bank policies in developed countries since 2008 are that these policies have caused a redistribution effect.
Of course, it will be like this; so what?
Any monetary policy action will redistribute wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, and reducing interest rates is beneficial to borrowers.
Importers like a strong exchange rate, while exporters like a weak exchange rate.
To be effective, monetary policy must have different effects on different groups at different times.
This is not an error; this is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also say that the central bank has failed to achieve the inflation target in any case, so its activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
They even put these self-contradictory criticisms in one sentence, as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks but causing casualties.
The fact is that major central banks around the world have achieved outstanding success in keeping prices stable and maintaining currency purchasing power during and after the global financial crisis — — and this is not at all negligible.
If not for their intervention, their economies would face catastrophic deflation, sharp declines in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
It is obvious that strong action is the correct approach to dealing with a crisis (what the central bank did in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another matter).
In a system that uses an elastic currency without inherent value, in order for the purchasing power of the currency to remain roughly unchanged over time, the quantity of the currency must also change over time.
Therefore, price stability, and not the quantity of money, is the key issue.
The expansion of the central bank's balance sheet reflects the depth of the problems many economies have faced since 2008.
In this context, the central bank has taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no "activism" here; only an eternal mission to be accomplished.
If you think this conclusion is arrogant, then let me provide some evidence.
The people vote with their wallets.
If their purchasing power is severely damaged after 2008, they will naturally seek to exchange their currency (into other currencies, precious metals, or other savings methods).
This is rare to see in the developed world.
Of course, many central banks have not achieved their inflation targets.
(Central banks usually define an ideal economic "temperature" as an inflation rate of around 2%.
) But this is certainly unpleasant, but it will not lead to a disaster, especially considering that the decline in prices is partly due to supply — — rather than demand — — shocks, such as a collapse in oil prices all the way.
This shock is beneficial to consumers, and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil importers.
Consider this scenario.
Some enterprise plans to increase sales by 2%, but the manager can only achieve this in the form of continuous two-year, each year increase by 1%.
Will you think this enterprise failed?
Probably not.
After all, private company plans and actual profits and income are easy to produce a 10% or more deviation.
Most companies' business environment variables are far below that of the central bank.
Since that's the case, how can you expect the central bank to achieve its inflation target precisely regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I did not say the central bank should not try to work towards their targets.
They absolutely should.
Furthermore, they absolutely should not make inflation expectations unstable.
However, when judging the central bank, people need to maintain appropriate proportions.
They do need to stop saying things that are not true - that the central bank's policy arsenal not only can be exhausted, but has almost been exhausted.
Monetary policymakers have enough weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal to use as they see fit.
These weapons have different calibers, and their effects also vary at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economic bodies in all situations.
But theoretically, the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is unlimited.
The central bank governor should tell their ignorant critics, "That's enough."
Our critics can't explain in a clear and believable way why price stability is the wrong target, what the key target the central bank should pursue; and what sharply different measures they should have taken since 2008.
There is a simple reason for this: The central bank's policies in developed countries since the crisis have been correct policies.
After all, that policy pulled our economies back from the cliff.
You're welcome.
